51 y/o M with ICM s/p BiVAICD, Stage D/Class III HFrEF s/p HMIII (2021-10-24), CAD s/p PCI to RCA 2014, paroxysmal Afib, ESRD on HD MWF, recent RLE cellulitis and recent multiple admissions over the past few months. In addition, he has DM, HTN, chronic gout, and anxiety being treated as active problems this visit.
He presents to ER with chief c/o epigastric pain that started yesterday, severe in intensity, non-radiating, associated with nausea and dyspnea. He further notes increased SOA since Thanksgiving. He notes that he had been drinking "a lot" of fluids. Denies LVAD alarms. Denies F/C/NS. No chest pain, pressure, tightness or heaviness. No diarrhea or constipation.

Pt admitted for SOB and abdominal pain. SOB and abdominal pain improved with HD on 11/29. GI consulted for epigastric pain, no intervention needed, if pain persistent can pursue further work up as outpatient with EGD/ CTA etc per GI recs. Pt reports complete resolution of abdominal pain and SOB and wanting to go home. Driveline dressing saturated with serous drainage, no active oozing noted. CT abdomen unremarkable. Would recommend daily dressing changes using VAD dressing kit. Bp was elevated this am, resumed home medication and MAP improved to 90. No medication changes made during this admission. Pt to continue HD MWF. Followed by nephrology.
Discharge plan has been discussed with patient, and he agrees to discharge at this time. Discharge instructions have been provided and patient verbalized his understanding. Discharge plan has been discussed with attending Dr. Pahwa and patient is stable for discharge home at this time.

Dialysis patient. Additional History: Hypertension. Congestive heart failure.

Isovue 370 100 mL was administered intravenously.
Automated mA/kV exposure control was utilized and patient examination was performed
in strict accordance with principles of ALARA.
RADIATION AMOUNT: 2180.45 mGy-cm.

FINDINGS:
Abdomen:
Bilateral gynecomastia. Mild elevation right hemidiaphragm. Overlying mild volume
loss in the right middle lobe and right lower lobe. Lung bases are otherwise
clear. No pleural fluid. Left ventricular assist device is seen. ICD leads also
present, biventricular.
Slight nodular contour of the liver possible early cirrhotic change. Probable
diffuse hepatic steatosis. No focal hepatic mass. No CT evidence of
cholelithiasis. No biliary ductal dilatation. The spleen is mildly enlarged
measuring 14 cm without mass. There are scattered calcifications in the spleen
consistent with old granulomatous disease. Mild bilateral cortical thinning of
both kidneys without hydronephrosis, mass or calculus. The adrenal glands are
normal. No ureteral stones.
Scattered subcentimeter retroperitoneal and small bowel mesenteric lymph nodes.
Mildly enlarged porta hepatis lymph node 1.5 cm short axis, probably benign such as
in the setting of chronic liver inflammation such as steatohepatitis. There is no
free air. Abdominal aorta is not aneurysmal.

Minimal sliding hiatal hernia. The stomach is otherwise unremarkable. No bowel
obstruction or ileus. Moderate colonic stool. There is no free fluid. Mild
bilateral inguinal adenopathy, for example on the left on image 103 measures 2.5 x

Nausea and Vomiting, Adult
Nausea is feeling sick to your stomach or feeling that you are about to throw up (vomit). Vomiting is when food in your stomach is thrown up and out of the mouth. Throwing up can make you feel weak. It can also make you lose too much water in your body (get dehydrated). If you lose too much water in your body, you may:
• Feel tired.
• Feel thirsty.
• Have a dry mouth.
• Have cracked lips.
• Go pee (urinate) less often.
Older adults and people with other diseases or a weak body defense Swanson (immune Swanson) are at higher risk for losing too much water in the body. If you feel sick to your stomach and you throw up, it is important to follow instructions from your doctor about how to take care of yourself.
Follow these instructions at home:
Watch your symptoms for any changes. Tell your doctor about them. Follow these instructions to care for yourself at home.
Eating and drinking
• Take an ORS (oral rehydration solution). This is a drink that is sold at pharmacies and stores.
• Drink clear fluids in small amounts as you are able, such as:
◦ Water.
◦ Ice chips.
◦ Fruit juice that has water added (diluted fruit juice).
◦ Low-calorie sports drinks.
• Eat bland, easy-to-digest foods in small amounts as you are able, such as:
◦ Bananas.
◦ Applesauce.
◦ Rice.
◦ Low-fat (lean) meats.
◦ Toast.
◦ Crackers.
• Avoid drinking fluids that have a lot of sugar or caffeine in them. This includes energy drinks, sports drinks, and soda.
• Avoid alcohol.
• Avoid spicy or fatty foods.
General instructions
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Drink enough fluid to keep your pee (urine) pale yellow.
• Wash your hands often with soap and water. If you cannot use soap and water, use hand sanitizer.
• Make sure that all people in your home wash their hands well and often.
• Rest at home while you get better.
• Watch your condition for any changes.
• Take slow and deep breaths when you feel sick to your stomach.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Contact a doctor if:
• Your symptoms get worse.
• You have new symptoms.
• You have a fever.
• You cannot drink fluids without throwing up.
• You feel sick to your stomach for more than 2 days.
• You feel light-headed or dizzy.
• You have a headache.
• You have muscle cramps.
• You have a rash.
• You have pain while peeing.
Get help right away if:
• You have pain in your chest, neck, arm, or jaw.
• You feel very weak or you pass out (faint).
• You throw up again and again.
• You have throw up that is bright red or looks like black coffee grounds.
• You have bloody or black poop (stools) or poop that looks like tar.
• You have a very bad headache, a stiff neck, or both.
• You have very bad pain, cramping, or bloating in your belly (abdomen).
• You have trouble breathing.
• You are breathing very quickly.
• Your heart is beating very quickly.
• Your skin feels cold and clammy.
• You feel confused.
• You have signs of losing too much water in your body, such as:
◦ Dark pee, very little pee, or no pee.
◦ Cracked lips.
◦ Dry mouth.
◦ Sunken eyes.
◦ Sleepiness.
◦ Weakness.
These symptoms may be an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
• Nausea is feeling sick to your stomach or feeling that you are about to throw up (vomit). Vomiting is when food in your stomach is thrown up and out of the mouth.
• Follow instructions from your doctor about eating and drinking to keep from losing too much water in your body.
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Contact your doctor if your symptoms get worse or you have new symptoms.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Heart Failure, Self Care
Heart failure is a serious condition. This sheet explains things you need to do to take care of yourself at home. To help you stay as healthy as possible, you may be asked to change your diet, take certain medicines, and make other changes in your life. Your doctor may also give you more specific instructions. If you have problems or questions, call your doctor.
What are the risks?
Having heart failure makes it more likely for you to have some problems. These problems can get worse if you do not take good care of yourself. Problems may include:
• Blood clotting problems. This may cause a stroke.
• Damage to the kidneys, liver, or lungs.
• Abnormal heart rhythms.
Supplies needed:
• Scale for weighing yourself.
• Blood pressure monitor.
• Notebook.
• Medicines.
How to care for yourself when you have heart failure
Medicines
Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor. Take your medicines every day.
• Do not stop taking your medicine unless your doctor tells you to do so.
• Do not skip any medicines.
• Get your prescriptions refilled before you run out of medicine. This is important.
Eating and drinking
• Eat heart-healthy foods. Talk with a diet specialist (dietitian) to create an eating plan.
• Choose foods that:
◦ Have no trans fat.
◦ Are low in saturated fat and cholesterol.
• Choose healthy foods, such as:
◦ Fresh or frozen fruits and vegetables.
◦ Fish.
◦ Low-fat (lean) meats.
◦ Legumes, such as beans, peas, and lentils.
◦ Fat-free or low-fat dairy products.
◦ Whole-grain foods.
◦ High-fiber foods.
• Limit salt (sodium) if told by your doctor. Ask your diet specialist to tell you which seasonings are healthy for your heart.
• Cook in healthy ways instead of frying. Healthy ways of cooking include roasting, grilling, broiling, baking, poaching, steaming, and stir-frying.
• Limit how much fluid you drink, if told by your doctor.
Alcohol use
• Do not drink alcohol if:
◦ Your doctor tells you not to drink.
◦ Your heart was damaged by alcohol, or you have very bad heart failure.
◦ You are pregnant, may be pregnant, or are planning to become pregnant.
• If you drink alcohol:
◦ Limit how much you use to:
▪ 0–1 drink a day for women.
▪ 0–2 drinks a day for men.
◦ Be aware of how much alcohol is in your drink. In the U.S., one drink equals one 12 oz bottle of beer (355 mL), one 5 oz glass of wine (148 mL), or one 1½ oz glass of hard liquor (44 mL).
Lifestyle
• Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco, such as cigarettes, e-cigarettes, and chewing tobacco. If you need help quitting, ask your doctor.
◦ Do not use nicotine gum or patches before talking to your doctor.
• Do not use illegal drugs.
• Lose weight if told by your doctor.
• Do physical activity if told by your doctor. Talk to your doctor before you begin an exercise if:
◦ You are an older adult.
◦ You have very bad heart failure.
• Learn to manage stress. If you need help, ask your doctor.
• Get rehab (rehabilitation) to help you stay independent and to help with your quality of life.
• Plan time to rest when you get tired.
Check weight and blood pressure
• Weigh yourself every day. This will help you to know if fluid is building up in your body.
◦ Weigh yourself every morning after you pee (urinate) and before you eat breakfast.
◦ Wear the same amount of clothing each time.
◦ Write down your daily weight. Give your record to your doctor.
• Check and write down your blood pressure as told by your doctor.
• Check your pulse as told by your doctor.
Dealing with very hot and very cold weather
• If it is very hot:
◦ Avoid activities that take a lot of energy.
◦ Use air conditioning or fans, or find a cooler place.
◦ Avoid caffeine and alcohol.
◦ Wear clothing that is loose-fitting, lightweight, and light-colored.
• If it is very cold:
◦ Avoid activities that take a lot of energy.
◦ Layer your clothes.
◦ Wear mittens or gloves, a hat, and a scarf when you go outside.
◦ Avoid alcohol.
Follow these instructions at home:
• Stay up to date with shots (vaccines). Get pneumococcal and flu (influenza) shots.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Contact a doctor if:
• You gain weight quickly.
• You have increasing shortness of breath.
• You cannot do your normal activities.
• You get tired easily.
• You cough a lot.
• You don't feel like eating or feel like you may vomit (nauseous).
• You become puffy (swell) in your hands, feet, ankles, or belly (abdomen).
• You cannot sleep well because it is hard to breathe.
• You feel like your heart is beating fast (palpitations).
• You get dizzy when you stand up.
Get help right away if:
• You have trouble breathing.
• You or someone else notices a change in your behavior, such as having trouble staying awake.
• You have chest pain or discomfort.
• You pass out (faint).
These symptoms may be an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
• Heart failure is a serious condition. To care for yourself, you may have to change your diet, take medicines, and make other lifestyle changes.
• Take your medicines every day. Do not stop taking them unless your doctor tells you to do so.
• Eat heart-healthy foods, such as fresh or frozen fruits and vegetables, fish, lean meats, legumes, fat-free or low-fat dairy products, and whole-grain or high-fiber foods.
• Ask your doctor if you can drink alcohol. You may have to stop alcohol use if you have very bad heart failure.
• Contact your doctor if you gain weight quickly or feel that your heart is beating too fast. Get help right away if you pass out, or have chest pain or trouble breathing.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Abdominal Pain, Adult
Many things can cause belly (abdominal) pain. Most times, belly pain is not dangerous. Many cases of belly pain can be watched and treated at home. Sometimes, though, belly pain is serious. Your doctor will try to find the cause of your belly pain.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Do not take medicines that help you poop (laxatives) unless told by your doctor.
General instructions
• Watch your belly pain for any changes.
• Drink enough fluid to keep your pee (urine) pale yellow.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Contact a doctor if:
• Your belly pain changes or gets worse.
• You are not hungry, or you lose weight without trying.
• You are having trouble pooping (constipated) or have watery poop (diarrhea) for more than 2–3 days.
• You have pain when you pee or poop.
• Your belly pain wakes you up at night.
• Your pain gets worse with meals, after eating, or with certain foods.
• You are vomiting and cannot keep anything down.
• You have a fever.
• You have blood in your pee.
Get help right away if:
• Your pain does not go away as soon as your doctor says it should.
• You cannot stop vomiting.
• Your pain is only in areas of your belly, such as the right side or the left lower part of the belly.
• You have bloody or black poop, or poop that looks like tar.
• You have very bad pain, cramping, or bloating in your belly.
• You have signs of not having enough fluid or water in your body (dehydration), such as:
◦ Dark pee, very little pee, or no pee.
◦ Cracked lips.
◦ Dry mouth.
◦ Sunken eyes.
◦ Sleepiness.
◦ Weakness.
• You have trouble breathing or chest pain.
Summary
• Many cases of belly pain can be watched and treated at home.
• Watch your belly pain for any changes.
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Contact a doctor if your belly pain changes or gets worse.
• Get help right away if you have very bad pain, cramping, or bloating in your belly.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
